question.value:
We will include studies meeting the following criteria: 
(1) participants do not meet criteria for current clinical episode of a depressive disorder at baseline, as established with a diagnostic interview by a trained interviewer or clinician;
(2) participants are assigned at random to a psychological preventive intervention or a control group;
(3) the incidence in the intervention and control conditions at follow-up (at least 3 months after randomization) is measured through a diagnostic interview by a trained interviewer or clinician;
(4) sufficient data are reported to calculate the incidence rates in the intervention and control conditions.
Any control group is acceptable, as long as it is defined by the researchers as a control group.
Trials on relapse prevention in which all participants have (partially) recovered from a depressive disorder after recent treatment will be excluded. Trials in which a history of previous depressive episodes was not used as an inclusion criterion were included in the current meta-analysis. This means that in some trials participants are included if they had had a depression before.
Trials in which a subpopulation has no depressive disorders can be included when all relevant data are reported for the subgroup without depressive disorders.
Trials in which participants receive treatment for another mental disorder will be excluded.
Staged inclusion is allowed, meaning that in universal or selective prevention, diagnoses are only made in those participants who score above a cut-off on a self-rating depression measure.

